## Summary

Implement the SM-2 spaced repetition algorithm for scheduling items across drill sessions. After each drill session, update each item's ease factor, interval, and next review date based on how well the user recalled it.

## Implementation Details

### 1. SM-2 algorithm

#### `lib/domain/services/srs_scheduler.dart`

The SM-2 algorithm (used by Anki and many SRS systems):

```dart
class SrsScheduler {
  /// Update progress after a drill response.
  ///
  /// [quality] — response quality mapped from drill score:
  ///   score >= 0.8 → quality 5 (perfect)
  ///   score >= 0.7 → quality 4 (correct with hesitation)
  ///   score >= 0.6 → quality 3 (correct with difficulty)
  ///   score >= 0.4 → quality 2 (incorrect but close)
  ///   score >= 0.2 → quality 1 (incorrect)
  ///   score < 0.2  → quality 0 (complete failure)
  UserProgress updateProgress(UserProgress current, double drillScore) {
    final quality = _scoreToQuality(drillScore);
    final now = DateTime.now();

    // New ease factor (minimum 1.3)
    var newEase = current.easeFactor +
        (0.1 - (5 - quality) * (0.08 + (5 - quality) * 0.02));
    if (newEase < 1.3) newEase = 1.3;

    int newIntervalSeconds;
    int newRepCount;

    if (quality < 3) {
      // Failed — reset to beginning
      newRepCount = 0;
      newIntervalSeconds = 60; // 1 minute (will show up again soon)
    } else {
      newRepCount = current.repetitionCount + 1;

      if (newRepCount == 1) {
        newIntervalSeconds = 60 * 60; // 1 hour
      } else if (newRepCount == 2) {
        newIntervalSeconds = 60 * 60 * 6; // 6 hours
      } else if (newRepCount == 3) {
        newIntervalSeconds = 60 * 60 * 24; // 1 day
      } else {
        // After 3rd rep: interval * ease factor
        newIntervalSeconds =
            (current.intervalSeconds * newEase).round();
      }
    }

    // Cap maximum interval at 180 days
    final maxInterval = 60 * 60 * 24 * 180;
    if (newIntervalSeconds > maxInterval) {
      newIntervalSeconds = maxInterval;
    }

    return UserProgress(
      itemId: current.itemId,
      easeFactor: newEase,
      intervalSeconds: newIntervalSeconds,
      nextReviewAt: now.add(Duration(seconds: newIntervalSeconds)),
      repetitionCount: newRepCount,
      lastScore: drillScore,
      lastReviewedAt: now,
    );
  }

  int _scoreToQuality(double score) {
    if (score >= 0.8) return 5;
    if (score >= 0.7) return 4;
    if (score >= 0.6) return 3;
    if (score >= 0.4) return 2;
    if (score >= 0.2) return 1;
    return 0;
  }
}
```

### 2. Interval progression

For a consistently correct learner (quality 5, ease ~2.5):

| Rep # | Interval | Human-readable |
|-------|----------|---------------|
| 1     | 3600s    | 1 hour        |
| 2     | 21600s   | 6 hours       |
| 3     | 86400s   | 1 day         |
| 4     | 216000s  | ~2.5 days     |
| 5     | 540000s  | ~6 days       |
| 6     | 1350000s | ~16 days      |
| 7     | 3375000s | ~39 days      |

This progression is gentler than strict SM-2 for the first 3 reps, then follows the standard formula.

