## Summary

Extend the DrillEngine to support dialog simulation drills. The AI plays the tutor's side of a Korean conversation, and the user responds as the student. This exercises conversational flow, listening comprehension, and contextual recall — the most Pimsleur-like drill type.

## Implementation Details

### 1. Dialog data model (already in Drift from #18)

```
DialogScripts: id, sessionId, title, description, difficulty
DialogTurns: id, dialogId, turnOrder, speakerRole (tutor|student), korean, english
```

A typical dialog has 4-8 turns alternating between tutor and student.

### 2. DialogDrillItem

Extend `DrillItem` to hold dialog context:

```dart
class DialogDrillItem extends DrillItem {
  final String dialogId;
  final String dialogTitle;
  final List<DialogTurn> turns;
  int currentTurnIndex = 0;

  DialogDrillItem({
    required super.lessonItem,
    required super.progress,
    required this.dialogId,
    required this.dialogTitle,
    required this.turns,
    super.drillType = DrillType.dialogSimulation,
    // promptEnglish and expectedKorean update per turn
    required super.promptEnglish,
    required super.expectedKorean,
  });

  /// Get the current turn pair (tutor line + student response)
  DialogTurnPair? get currentTurnPair {
    if (currentTurnIndex >= turnPairs.length) return null;
    return turnPairs[currentTurnIndex];
  }

  /// Pre-computed pairs of (tutor says X, student says Y)
  late final List<DialogTurnPair> turnPairs = _buildTurnPairs();

  List<DialogTurnPair> _buildTurnPairs() {
    final pairs = <DialogTurnPair>[];
    for (var i = 0; i < turns.length - 1; i++) {
      if (turns[i].speakerRole == 'tutor' && turns[i + 1].speakerRole == 'student') {
        pairs.add(DialogTurnPair(
          tutorTurn: turns[i],
          studentTurn: turns[i + 1],
        ));
      }
    }
    return pairs;
  }

  /// Advance to the next turn pair. Returns true if more pairs remain.
  bool advanceTurn() {
    currentTurnIndex++;
    if (currentTurnIndex < turnPairs.length) {
      // Update prompt/expected for next turn
      final pair = turnPairs[currentTurnIndex];
      // These are final in DrillItem, so we'll use a different approach
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }

  bool get isDialogComplete => currentTurnIndex >= turnPairs.length;
}

class DialogTurnPair {
  final DialogTurn tutorTurn;
  final DialogTurn studentTurn;

  DialogTurnPair({required this.tutorTurn, required this.studentTurn});
}

class DialogTurn {
  final int turnOrder;
  final String speakerRole;
  final String korean;
  final String english;

  DialogTurn({
    required this.turnOrder,
    required this.speakerRole,
    required this.korean,
    required this.english,
  });
}
```

### 3. DrillEngine dialog flow

Add dialog handling to the state machine. New phase flow for dialogs:

```
presenting_scene    → TTS speaks scene description ("You're at a restaurant...")
presenting_tutor    → TTS speaks tutor's Korean line
waiting             → brief pause
listening           → STT captures student's Korean response
evaluating          → score against expected student line
feedback            → show result
presenting_tutor    → next turn pair (loop until dialog complete)
feedback            → dialog complete, show overall score
```

```dart
// In DrillEngine:

Future<void> _presentDialogItem(DialogDrillItem item) async {
  if (item.currentTurnIndex == 0) {
    // First turn: introduce the scene
    state = state.copyWith(
      phase: DrillEnginePhase.presenting,
      dialogContext: 'Scene: ${item.dialogTitle}',
    );
    await _tts.speakEnglish(item.dialogTitle);
    await Future.delayed(const Duration(seconds: 1));
  }

  final pair = item.currentTurnPair;
  if (pair == null) {
    // Dialog complete
    await _handleDialogComplete(item);
    return;
  }

  // Speak tutor's line in Korean
  state = state.copyWith(
    phase: DrillEnginePhase.presenting,
    currentDialogTurn: pair,
  );
  await _tts.speakKorean(pair.tutorTurn.korean, rate: 0.45);

  // Wait, then listen for student's response
  state = state.copyWith(phase: DrillEnginePhase.waiting);
  await Future.delayed(const Duration(milliseconds: 700));

  state = state.copyWith(phase: DrillEnginePhase.listening);
  final response = await _stt.listenForKorean(
    timeout: const Duration(seconds: 15), // longer for dialog
  );

  // Evaluate against expected student line
  state = state.copyWith(phase: DrillEnginePhase.evaluating, userResponse: response);

  final evaluation = await _evaluator.evaluate(
    expected: pair.studentTurn.korean,
    actual: response ?? '',
    english: pair.studentTurn.english,
    difficulty: item.lessonItem.difficulty,
  );

  state = state.copyWith(
    phase: DrillEnginePhase.feedback,
    lastEvaluation: evaluation,
  );

  // After feedback, advance to next turn
  // (user taps continue or auto-advance)
}

Future<void> continueDialogAfterFeedback(DialogDrillItem item) async {
  if (item.advanceTurn()) {
    await _presentDialogItem(item);
  } else {
    await _handleDialogComplete(item);
  }
}

Future<void> _handleDialogComplete(DialogDrillItem item) async {
  // Compute average score across all turns
  // Update progress
  // Move to next item in queue
  await _presentNext();
}
```

### 4. Dialog scheduling

Dialogs are scheduled as single items in the drill queue, but they expand into multiple turns during execution. The scheduler treats them like any other drill item for Pimsleur intervals.

```dart
// In DrillScheduler:
if (item.type == DrillType.dialogSimulation) {
  // Schedule at same intervals, but each "presentation" is the full dialog
  // Weight dialog items slightly lower in frequency (they take longer)
